ðŸ”¹ $ can indicate variable expansion:

name="world"
echo "Hello, $name"  # â†’ Hello, world
ðŸ”¹ $() is for command substitution:
This is one of the most powerful uses of $!

date_output=$(date)
echo "Current date is: $date_output"
Or inline:

echo "Today is $(date +%A)"
That runs the command inside $(...) and substitutes the output into the line.

ðŸ”¹ $ can also be part of positional parameters and special variables:
$1, $2, etc. â†’ script arguments

$# â†’ number of arguments

$? â†’ exit status of last command

$$ â†’ PID of the script

$! â†’ PID of the last backgrounded process

ðŸ”¹ $ can be used with arithmetic expansion:
echo $((2 + 3))  # â†’ 5
